This is an introductory tutorial for DICOMautomaton.

Click 'Continue' to proceed to the next step.
---
In this tutorial, we'll focus on basic interactive usage of DICOMautomaton.

Note that this is just a guide. You can view it as-is ... but it will work best if you follow along!
---
DICOMautomaton has a modular design such that different components can be viewed, analyzed, or transformed separately.

Examples of components include medical images (e.g., CT, MR, PET), 3D surface meshes, 3D point clouds, radiotherapy
treatment plans, data tables, and 3D-to-3D (mathematical) transformations, among others.

In this tutorial, we will create an image array.
---
Besides components, DICOMautomaton also has a concept of 'operations', which can be performed to add, remove, or alter
components.

Operations often need to be configured in some way before being invoked.

For example, to copy a set of images, the copy operation needs to know which set of images to copy.
---
A series of operations can be chained together to produce a meaningful action.

There a a few ways to do this, but the most straightforward is to create a script which can be executed like a program
inside the interactive viewer.

Let's demonstrate invoking a pre-written action now. The action will create a new image array component.
---
In the menu bar, click 'Actions', then 'images', then 'make new image array'.

base64png:
---
After clicking, you should see the 'Images' viewer window appear.

Besides the 'Images' viewer, you should also see an 'Image Navigation' window. You can use this window to navigate the
image array.

Note that we created an *array* of images -- this set of images fills a 3D volume.

Also note that the images are uniform and do not show anything useful. We'll come back to this point later.

base64png:

base64png:
---
Now let's dig into the action script. Our aim is to alter the script to produce a more interesting set of images.

In the menu bar, click 'Script', then 'Edit Action Script', then 'images', then 'make new image array'. The script
editor should appear.

base64png:
---
This action script is relatively simple. There is a single operation performed (GenerateSyntheticImages). However, there are
lots of parameters.

base64png:
---
We'll change the 'StipleValue' parameter so that a checkerboard pattern appears on each image.

Change the value to '1.0'.

base64png:
---
To invoke the modified script, we'll need to compile it first.

In the Script Editor window, click the 'Validate' button. This parses the script and looks for syntax errors, but does
not actually invoke the script.

Do you see the 'Script Feedback' window appear? It contains information about the script.

base64png:

base64png:
---
Now click the 'Run' button. It should only take a second or two to complete.

Our modified script created a new image array, but it did not alter the existing array. So you'll need to use the 'Image
Navigation' window to show the new array.

base64png:
---
You should now see a fine checkerboard pattern in the image.

Each image contains thousands of pixels, so depending on your screen resolution you might see a solid colour or a
moire pattern. Try zooming in!

base64png:

---
There are many supported operations that span a wide variety of functionality, including operations that can invoke
other operations and operations that create temporary views.

We won't go into any more operations in this tutorial. However, every operation is documented. If you're ready to begin
creating your own scripts, check out the operation documentation or the reference guide.

If you're ready to explore scripting, there are tutorials for that too!
